This award provided travel support (airfare, ground transportation, housing, and registration) for U.S. students and early career scientists to attend the Seventh Solar Information Processing Workshop in Belgium.

The overarching goal of this workshop was to foster interdisciplinary communication between space physics and information processing communities in order to stress the importance of rigorous inference methods to enable quantitative analysis.  More specifically, the objectives of the conference were to provide the solar and heliospheric community with the following:


- Discussion on the solar wind characteristics including methodological issues and data analysis techniques of the solar wind turbulence properties;


- An understanding of the new data analysis challenges brought by the upcoming Solar Orbiter and Solar Probe missions;


- A discussion on current methods for space weather prediction and their possible improvements using dedicated machine learning algorithms for example;


- A review on the most recent methods in tracking of small scale elements, and a discussion on which signatures of solar dynamo effects can be retrieved from a detailed tracking of surface magnetic features;

- An introduction to Bayesian inference in the context of power law model estimation.



In addition, it provided travel support for a U.S. student to attend the International Conference on Acoustics Speech, and Signal Processing (ICASSP) where he presented a paper on a novel approach to geospace imaging.  The student's participation at this conference enabled him to foster interdisciplinary communication between space physics and information processing communities in order to stress the importance of rigorous inference methods to enable quantitative analysis of space science data. 

